great Jimmie Lunceford back

00:17:58.180 --> 00:18:02.410
in the early '40s, late '30s.

00:18:02.410 --> 00:18:06.210
And when I transferred
to Manassas,

00:18:06.210 --> 00:18:07.340
I didn't choose music.

00:18:07.340 --> 00:18:10.810
It sounds corny, but it
chose me because when

00:18:10.810 --> 00:18:13.940
people were studying Chopin
etudes-- no shame in my game,

00:18:13.940 --> 00:18:15.490
as BB King talked about.

00:18:15.490 --> 00:18:18.600
I was chopping and picking
and pulling cotton.

00:18:18.600 --> 00:18:21.790
So one day I heard a little girl
play a song on all the black

00:18:21.790 --> 00:18:26.800
keys called, "I Stuck my
Dolly-- D-O-L-L-Y-- in the Mud,"

00:18:26.800 --> 00:18:30.040
and that's the first thing
I learned. (HUMMING SONG)

00:18:30.040 --> 00:18:33.580
So when I got to Frank Strozier,
one of my closest friends,

00:18:33.580 --> 00:18:36.780
told me, why don't you come
to Manassas High School?

00:18:36.780 --> 00:18:40.340
And I transferred from
Douglas to Manassas,

00:18:40.340 --> 00:18:44.110
of my classmates were Booker
Little, George Coleman, Frank

00:18:44.110 --> 00:18:47.860
Storzier, Charles Lord,
Hank Crawford, Lewis Smith.

00:18:47.860 --> 00:18:49.330
Isaac Hayes was later.

00:18:49.330 --> 00:18:53.180
And we were taught by a
man named Matthew Garrett,

00:18:53.180 --> 00:18:54.246
and he had a daughter.

00:18:54.246 --> 00:18:57.010
Her name was Denise Gary,
who's now Dee Dee Bridgewater.

00:18:57.010 --> 00:19:00.350
Dee Dee Bridgewater's father
was our band director.

00:19:00.350 --> 00:19:02.240
So anyway, I knew three songs.

00:19:02.240 --> 00:19:04.560
1951 is when I started.

00:19:04.560 --> 00:19:07.280
And when I moved
to Chicago I've met

00:19:07.280 --> 00:19:09.740
Spike Lee's father, Bill Lee.

00:19:09.740 --> 00:19:12.200
Bill Lee, one of the
greatest all-around

00:19:12.200 --> 00:19:14.290
geniuses that ever
lived, but he's always

00:19:14.290 --> 00:19:16.590
been anti-amplification,
and so he

00:19:16.590 --> 00:19:17.860
wasn't born with a big sound.

00:19:17.860 --> 00:19:19.430
But when I went to
Chicago-- that's

00:19:19.430 --> 00:19:21.390
one the greatest
cities in the world.

00:19:21.390 --> 00:19:24.986
That's how I learned how
to conceptualize music.

00:19:24.986 --> 00:19:26.360
Then, when I moved
to New York, I

00:19:26.360 --> 00:19:28.720
had a better
understanding about it.

00:19:28.720 --> 00:19:30.740
And as I said, the first
night in New York City,

00:19:30.740 --> 00:19:34.070
Cannonball introduced me
to Harry "Sweets" Edison.

00:19:34.070 --> 00:19:35.920
And old timers
then, they assumed

00:19:35.920 --> 00:19:37.850
if you're a musician--
Kurt can tell you--

00:19:37.850 --> 00:19:39.850
you get on the [INAUDIBLE],
you know everything.

00:19:39.850 --> 00:19:42.610
So Sweet says to me,
you want to play?

00:19:42.610 --> 00:19:44.320
I said, yeah.

00:19:44.320 --> 00:19:46.837
So he said, "Habit,"
eight by interjection.

00:19:46.837 --> 00:19:48.420
I said, well what
the heck is "Habit"?

00:19:48.420 --> 00:19:50.120
I knew how play eight
by interjection.

00:19:50.120 --> 00:19:52.042
The song was "Getting
to be a Habit with You."

00:19:52.042 --> 00:19:53.000
never played it before.

00:19:53.000 --> 00:19:53.960
I fumbled.

00:19:53.960 --> 00:19:55.100
Second chorus I had it.

00:19:55.100 --> 00:19:56.190
He said, you got the get.

00:19:56.190 --> 00:19:58.260
He took me right
back to Chicago.

00:19:58.260 --> 00:20:01.030
I made $250 a week
at the Blue Note.

00:20:01.030 --> 00:20:04.970
Now in case you young people
don't know how money that was,

00:20:04.970 --> 00:20:08.290
in 1959 I had $5,000.

00:20:08.290 --> 00:20:11.920
$2,500 in this shoe,
and $2,500 in that shoe.

00:20:11.920 --> 00:20:12.420
Why?

00:20:12.420 --> 00:20:15.960
Because that was so long ago,
you know these Ziploc bags

00:20:15.960 --> 00:20:17.297
that you take for granted?

00:20:17.297 --> 00:20:18.630
They weren't on the market then.

00:20:18.630 --> 00:20:20.709
They were being tested.

00:20:20.709 --> 00:20:22.375
And to show you how
much money that was,

00:20:22.375 --> 00:20:25.100
I'm going to fast forward
because once I get to talking,

00:20:25.100 --> 00:20:27.460
you can't stop me.

00:20:27.460 --> 00:20:31.480
The Four Seasons hotel which
starts at $750 a night,

00:20:31.480 --> 00:20:33.480
was $50 a week.

00:20:33.480 --> 00:20:36.400
The legendary
[INAUDIBLE] was 99 cents.

00:20:36.400 --> 00:20:37.600
That was the cover charge.

00:20:37.600 --> 00:20:40.410
So anyway, fast forward, and
I was blessed because I came.

00:20:40.410 --> 00:20:41.250
I was hustling.

00:20:41.250 --> 00:20:43.510
I promoted myself,
and I got a call

00:20:43.510 --> 00:20:46.160
to teach at William
Paterson in 1981,

00:20:46.160 --> 00:20:48.670
