MALE SPEAKER:
Thank you for that.

00:21:04.420 --> 00:21:06.340
Just on the topic of
learning, I guess,

00:21:06.340 --> 00:21:08.310
Harold was Eric's teacher.

00:21:08.310 --> 00:21:13.261
He was my teacher, and
one of the ideas in jazz

00:21:13.261 --> 00:21:15.260
and just kind of the way
that the music evolves,

00:21:15.260 --> 00:21:18.060
it's if you hear
it, you can have it.

00:21:18.060 --> 00:21:21.220
It's this idea that
everything's right there for you

00:21:21.220 --> 00:21:24.390
to learn and try to
incorporate into your playing,

00:21:24.390 --> 00:21:26.976
and people just added ideas.

00:21:26.976 --> 00:21:28.600
They find a way to
make them their own.

00:21:28.600 --> 00:21:33.640
And over time, you get some
really unique contributions

00:21:33.640 --> 00:21:34.210
to the music.

00:21:34.210 --> 00:21:38.060
And it sounds a
little bit like-- I

00:21:38.060 --> 00:21:40.910
guess I'll make an internet
analogy-- there's open source

00:21:40.910 --> 00:21:41.420
code.

00:21:41.420 --> 00:21:43.950
There's things like Wikipedia
with a lot of people

00:21:43.950 --> 00:21:47.350
just kind of
collectively contributing

00:21:47.350 --> 00:21:48.940
in similar way as music.

00:21:52.680 --> 00:21:56.420
So tell me a little bit
about your experience

00:21:56.420 --> 00:21:57.240
working with Eric.

00:21:57.240 --> 00:21:59.370
I know you guys
met when Eric was

00:21:59.370 --> 00:22:01.800
in school at William
Paterson, but you've

00:22:01.800 --> 00:22:03.900
gone on to work a lot together.

00:22:03.900 --> 00:22:06.000
HAROLD MABERN: Yeah, he
left Indiana University

00:22:06.000 --> 00:22:11.980
and professor Dave
Baker told Rufus Reid.

00:22:11.980 --> 00:22:13.764
Rufus was a professor there.

00:22:13.764 --> 00:22:15.430
Then we got a young
tenor player coming,

00:22:15.430 --> 00:22:17.950
and we'd like for you
to see what you can do.

00:22:17.950 --> 00:22:20.180
So Rufus assigned
him to my class.

00:22:20.180 --> 00:22:22.240
And I always tell
the students, you

00:22:22.240 --> 00:22:24.650
should always have a
tape recorder with you

00:22:24.650 --> 00:22:26.560
and some manuscript paper.

00:22:26.560 --> 00:22:27.680
So Eric came in.

00:22:27.680 --> 00:22:29.560
I had him play
"Embraceable You."

00:22:29.560 --> 00:22:33.260
He'd never played it before in
his life, and what he played,

00:22:33.260 --> 00:22:36.300
believe me, was a
complete masterpiece.

00:22:36.300 --> 00:22:38.610
And unfortunately, I
didn't follow my own advice

00:22:38.610 --> 00:22:40.440
because I couldn't document it.

00:22:40.440 --> 00:22:44.724
And he was playing like Dexter
Gordon there, which is great.

00:22:44.724 --> 00:22:46.390
And I knew then, I
said to myself, well,

00:22:46.390 --> 00:22:48.440
this is an A student, really.

00:22:48.440 --> 00:22:49.790
And I told him three things.

00:22:49.790 --> 00:22:52.420
I said learn all your
standards in all the keys,

00:22:52.420 --> 00:22:54.690
and go see George
Coleman, and he did.

00:22:54.690 --> 00:22:56.785
He took two lessons,
and the rest

00:22:56.785 --> 00:22:59.720
is history, as they say--
very smart young man.

00:22:59.720 --> 00:23:02.230
And please don't try to pay
me, because I'm serious.

00:23:02.230 --> 00:23:05.980
This is one of the
smartest young man

00:23:05.980 --> 00:23:07.260
playing any kind of music.

00:23:07.260 --> 00:23:10.170
and he plays piano--
Ravel and Debussy and all.

00:23:10.170 --> 00:23:11.670
So it's a pleasure
working with him,

00:23:11.670 --> 00:23:12.878
and we learn from each other.

00:23:12.878 --> 00:23:15.750
Now we've been-- how many
CDs have we done together?

00:23:15.750 --> 00:23:18.554
On [INAUDIBLE], I'd say
we've made at least 20.

00:23:18.554 --> 00:23:20.845
ERIC ALEXANDER: But we've
probably been on at least 70.

00:23:20.845 --> 00:23:23.095
HAROLD MABERN: At least 70
together with other people,

00:23:23.095 --> 00:23:25.010
so I'm going to let him talk.

00:23:25.010 --> 00:23:26.610
