00:23:32.560 --> 00:23:37.532
That tune you mentioned, "I
Stuck My Dolly in the Mud?"

00:23:37.532 --> 00:23:39.060
See, I had a
different upbringing.

00:23:39.060 --> 00:23:41.236
We called that "Salvadore
Dali in the Mud."

00:23:41.236 --> 00:23:42.152
HAROLD MABERN: Really?

00:23:42.152 --> 00:23:42.916
ERIC ALEXANDER: Yeah.

00:23:42.916 --> 00:23:44.499
HAROLD MABERN: So
you know about this?

00:23:44.499 --> 00:23:45.699
I didn't know that.

00:23:45.699 --> 00:23:48.240
ERIC ALEXANDER: And what am I
supposed to be addressing here,

00:23:48.240 --> 00:23:50.680
Andrew?

00:23:50.680 --> 00:23:52.835
Harold was-- this is
his show, so let's keep.

00:23:52.835 --> 00:23:54.210
HAROLD MABERN:
No, it's our show.

00:23:54.210 --> 00:23:56.010
ERIC ALEXANDER:
Well, he's certainly

00:23:56.010 --> 00:23:59.740
the most influential
musical mentor

00:23:59.740 --> 00:24:01.130
that I've ever encountered.

00:24:01.130 --> 00:24:05.660
He took me, despite what
he says, from a point

00:24:05.660 --> 00:24:10.390
where I was absolutely green,
and saw some something in there

00:24:10.390 --> 00:24:12.730
and was always willing to
help and show me new ideas,

00:24:12.730 --> 00:24:16.950
and he's really the primary
reason for whatever I'm

00:24:16.950 --> 00:24:18.890
doing today or however I play.

00:24:18.890 --> 00:24:22.600
I thank Harold every day,
at least, in my mind,

00:24:22.600 --> 00:24:25.060
sometimes not to your face.

00:24:25.060 --> 00:24:25.670
I do.

00:24:25.670 --> 00:24:29.310
And it's funny; we've actually
been around each other now,

00:24:29.310 --> 00:24:32.410
if I think about the
years since I started

00:24:32.410 --> 00:24:36.650
working as a professional, I've
probably been next to this man

00:24:36.650 --> 00:24:40.130
more than any other person on
the planet, including my wife,

00:24:40.130 --> 00:24:41.640
and that probably
pisses her off.

00:24:41.640 --> 00:24:45.650
We're always on the
road doing something.

00:24:45.650 --> 00:24:46.634
It's really amazing.

00:24:46.634 --> 00:24:47.800
It's like a dream come true.

00:24:47.800 --> 00:24:49.940
I don't know what to say.

00:24:49.940 --> 00:24:55.310
Teaching and learning in jazz
is very different from other art

00:24:55.310 --> 00:24:59.290
forms or, in particular,
Western classical art music

00:24:59.290 --> 00:25:01.970
because it's not as pedagogical.

00:25:01.970 --> 00:25:04.500
Like Andrew said,
it's more about

00:25:04.500 --> 00:25:06.130
if you can hear
it and figure out

00:25:06.130 --> 00:25:09.370
what it is in sort of an
intuitive and personal way,

00:25:09.370 --> 00:25:11.600
then you can make it your own.

00:25:11.600 --> 00:25:15.930
And it just takes somebody to
continually show you things.

00:25:15.930 --> 00:25:18.770
They don't tell you how
to do it necessarily,

00:25:18.770 --> 00:25:22.640
but they show you
what it sounds like,

00:25:22.640 --> 00:25:25.400
and then eventually you
start to pick it up,

00:25:25.400 --> 00:25:29.240
and that's what he's been
doing for me for 25 years.

00:25:29.240 --> 00:25:31.110
MALE SPEAKER: Great, thank you.

