but it also has influence
some of the material

00:26:08.250 --> 00:26:10.170
that jazz musicians play
in the United States.

00:26:10.170 --> 00:26:12.950
And also there are great
musicians everywhere,

00:26:12.950 --> 00:26:17.420
and I think Kurt's latest
album captures a lot of that.

00:26:17.420 --> 00:26:20.832
So what can you tell us
about how that came together?

00:26:20.832 --> 00:26:22.790
KURT ELLING: Well, first
of all, hi, everybody.

00:26:22.790 --> 00:26:24.610
Happy to be here.

00:26:24.610 --> 00:26:28.779
Harold Mabern, great genius,
happy to be his side man

00:26:28.779 --> 00:26:29.320
this evening.

00:26:29.320 --> 00:26:30.106
It's wonderful.

00:26:30.106 --> 00:26:31.730
I'm happy to have a
little bit of time.

00:26:31.730 --> 00:26:34.730
It's an honor for me.

00:26:34.730 --> 00:26:36.760
Jazz is the ultimate
syncratic art

00:26:36.760 --> 00:26:40.770
form, which means
that any music,

00:26:40.770 --> 00:26:45.050
any sound that it encounters,
any rhythm any tradition,

00:26:45.050 --> 00:26:48.310
anything that it encounters
that it finds valuable,

00:26:48.310 --> 00:26:51.320
it can adopt and transform.

00:26:51.320 --> 00:26:53.284
And it transforms
itself, and it transforms

00:26:53.284 --> 00:26:54.325
that which it encounters.

00:26:57.130 --> 00:27:01.550
As Harold said, it was
born in the United States,

00:27:01.550 --> 00:27:04.830
but it was born of so many
different countries and so many

00:27:04.830 --> 00:27:05.830
different traditions.

00:27:05.830 --> 00:27:10.740
It was born of the collision
of cultures, largely, but not

00:27:10.740 --> 00:27:13.070
exclusively in New Orleans.

00:27:13.070 --> 00:27:16.320
It grew up in Chicago,
yet more collision

00:27:16.320 --> 00:27:20.000
of cultures-- collision
of African-- vast

00:27:20.000 --> 00:27:23.610
over-generalization--
collision of African rhythms

00:27:23.610 --> 00:27:28.510
with European harmonic
ideas and instrumentation.

00:27:28.510 --> 00:27:32.420
And it continues to
seek out new ideas,

00:27:32.420 --> 00:27:35.920
and it continues to grow in
all these different countries,

00:27:35.920 --> 00:27:38.350
having grown up in America.

00:27:38.350 --> 00:27:42.600
Dizzy Gillespie, back in
the day, goes down to Cuba

00:27:42.600 --> 00:27:45.770
and moves from hard
swinging everything

00:27:45.770 --> 00:27:48.640
to a whole new way
of thinking of music

00:27:48.640 --> 00:27:51.850
and calls it Afro Cuban music.

00:27:51.850 --> 00:27:57.080
And it puts a whole new gloss on
what he was about as an artist.

00:27:57.080 --> 00:28:00.600
And these days you have
artists around the world who

00:28:00.600 --> 00:28:05.530
have encountered jazz-- "jazz,"
quote unquote, American style--

00:28:05.530 --> 00:28:07.460
who have encountered
it, who have fallen

00:28:07.460 --> 00:28:11.110
in love with the great
pillar heroes of the music,

00:28:11.110 --> 00:28:14.840
and yet have brought their own
sensibilities to the music.

00:28:14.840 --> 00:28:17.270
So you have a whole
Scandinavian realm

00:28:17.270 --> 00:28:21.430
of artists who sound only like
themselves, who are informed

00:28:21.430 --> 00:28:24.740
by the American tradition but
bring their own identities

00:28:24.740 --> 00:28:27.250
to the music and have a
signature event that's

00:28:27.250 --> 00:28:28.520
happening up there.

00:28:28.520 --> 00:28:31.440
You have people in France
who make beautiful gypsy

00:28:31.440 --> 00:28:33.580
kind of sounding
jazz music, who swing

00:28:33.580 --> 00:28:34.910
in a way that belongs to them.

00:28:34.910 --> 00:28:36.860
You have cats now
who are working

00:28:36.860 --> 00:28:41.830
with Indian poly-rhythms, who
are a mixture of American cats

00:28:41.830 --> 00:28:45.350
and cats from India who are in
just moving the music forward

00:28:45.350 --> 00:28:48.560
in ways that nobody had
thought of even 10 years ago.

00:28:48.560 --> 00:28:51.790
And it's from the creative
juxtaposition of ideas

00:28:51.790 --> 00:28:54.730
that a lot of the
greatest sounds happen.

00:28:54.730 --> 00:28:58.350
So on my recording
"Passion World," since I've

00:28:58.350 --> 00:29:01.780
been out touring not nearly
as long as Dr. Mabern here,

00:29:01.780 --> 00:29:03.957
but I've been out for
about 20 years now,

00:29:03.957 --> 00:29:06.040
and I go to Europe all the
time, and I go to Asia,

00:29:06.040 --> 00:29:07.500
and I go to South
America and try

00:29:07.500 --> 00:29:11.455
to learn wherever I go,
who are the great players.

00:29:11.455 --> 00:29:13.830
Fans will come up afterwards,
oh, man, thank you so much.

00:29:13.830 --> 00:29:15.080
I say, hey, who's around here?

00:29:15.080 --> 00:29:17.890
Who can I stay
awake for tonight?

00:29:17.890 --> 00:29:20.680
And as I've done that I've
collected certain compositions,

00:29:20.680 --> 00:29:22.940
certain ways of
thinking about things

00:29:22.940 --> 00:29:25.230
and certain
international heroes,

00:29:25.230 --> 00:29:29.590
and I wanted to include them in
my own sound, in my own world,

00:29:29.590 --> 00:29:31.930
and I wanted to feature
them in a certain kind

00:29:31.930 --> 00:29:33.350
of a way in the United States.

00:29:33.350 --> 00:29:36.330
So on this recording we have
Till Bronner from Germany.

00:29:36.330 --> 00:29:41.060
We have Arturo Sandoval,
who's obviously many decades

00:29:41.060 --> 00:29:45.330
ago now moved up from
Cuba, Richard Galliano,

00:29:45.330 --> 00:29:49.310
incredible virtuoso
French accordion player.

00:29:49.310 --> 00:29:52.430
As a Chicagoan, I can always
hear the accordion [INAUDIBLE]

00:29:52.430 --> 00:29:55.940
all the Chicago cats because
of the Polish connection.

00:29:55.940 --> 00:29:57.330
Got a beautiful
thing from Poland

00:29:57.330 --> 00:30:01.430
from Pat Metheny,
orchestra from Germany.

00:30:01.430 --> 00:30:06.880
So we are Americans
who encounter the world

00:30:06.880 --> 00:30:08.630
and try to continue
learning, just

00:30:08.630 --> 00:30:12.780
as Dr. Mabern here continues
to learn from his students.

00:30:12.780 --> 00:30:15.239
And it's also
romantic, which is good

00:30:15.239 --> 00:30:17.030
because you know I'm
on your team for that.

00:30:17.030 --> 00:30:18.656
I want that to happen.

00:30:18.656 --> 00:30:22.624
[APPLAUSE]

00:30:24.454 --> 00:30:25.870
MALE SPEAKER: And
bringing it back

00:30:25.870 --> 00:30:30.250
to "Afro Blue" for a
moment, just, of course,

00:30:30.250 --> 00:30:32.780
this is improvised music,
and there's a structure,

00:30:32.780 --> 00:30:37.230
but what these guys are doing is
basically composing on the fly.

00:30:37.230 --> 00:30:40.350
And I heard a story
about one of the tunes

00:30:40.350 --> 00:30:45.410
that you did with Harold that
wasn't planned to happen.

00:30:45.410 --> 00:30:47.490
KURT ELLING: Yes, we
had several things,

00:30:47.490 --> 00:30:51.090
and I was so proud to get
the call in the first place,

00:30:51.090 --> 00:30:52.760
to jump in on a
couple of things that

00:30:52.760 --> 00:30:55.940
are more traditional that we'll
be doing a little bit later.

00:30:55.940 --> 00:31:01.044
But then, as I had my coat on--
this was January sometime--

00:31:01.044 --> 00:31:01.960
HAROLD MABERN: August.

00:31:01.960 --> 00:31:02.580
KURT ELLING: Was it August?

00:31:02.580 --> 00:31:04.038
I thought I was
putting my coat on.

00:31:04.038 --> 00:31:05.735
Really?

00:31:05.735 --> 00:31:07.597
HAROLD MABERN: That's OK.

00:31:07.597 --> 00:31:08.096
It's--

00:31:10.770 --> 00:31:14.154
KURT ELLING: It's what
we call a schmear.

00:31:14.154 --> 00:31:16.640
ERIC ALEXANDER: You might
have been hiding something.

00:31:16.640 --> 00:31:18.090
KURT ELLING: Maybe I was.

00:31:18.090 --> 00:31:22.550
I'm always hiding something,
So anyway, I was on my way out,

00:31:22.550 --> 00:31:25.400
and Harold started to--
I heard you talking

00:31:25.400 --> 00:31:27.797
about this other tune
that you want to do,

00:31:27.797 --> 00:31:29.880
and I don't remember how
it wasn't going to happen

00:31:29.880 --> 00:31:31.940
or was going to happen,
but you started playing.

00:31:31.940 --> 00:31:37.180
HAROLD MABERN: Originally
I had Norah Jones in mind.

00:31:37.180 --> 00:31:40.550
This is a true story, folks.

00:31:40.550 --> 00:31:42.740
Is it on?

00:31:42.740 --> 00:31:46.990
Originally this song is called
"You Needed Me" by Anne Murray,

00:31:46.990 --> 00:31:48.990
and George Coleman
kind of instigated this

00:31:48.990 --> 00:31:50.170
because he said, hey, Mabe.

00:31:50.170 --> 00:31:51.280
My friends call me Mabe.

00:31:51.280 --> 00:31:54.210
He said, do you ever play
that song "You Needed Me?"

00:31:54.210 --> 00:31:55.600
And I said, yeah.

00:31:55.600 --> 00:31:57.630
So we got to the day,
and I wanted Norah Jones,

00:31:57.630 --> 00:32:01.805
but Paul Stache felt that
maybe, stylistically speaking,

00:32:01.805 --> 00:32:03.057
it wouldn't be good for Norah.

00:32:03.057 --> 00:32:03.640
So I said, OK.

00:32:03.640 --> 00:32:04.944
So I told her.

00:32:04.944 --> 00:32:06.360
We call him Big
Red affectionately

00:32:06.360 --> 00:32:07.360
because of his red hair.

00:32:07.360 --> 00:32:10.010
So I said, well, come on, Big
Red, we've got to do this song.

00:32:10.010 --> 00:32:12.640
I said, you've got
to do Boots Randolph,

00:32:12.640 --> 00:32:14.680
because I was
determined-- true story.

00:32:14.680 --> 00:32:16.680
I guess you could say it
was kind of like, what,

00:32:16.680 --> 00:32:17.520
serendipity?

00:32:17.520 --> 00:32:20.730
Kurt had his-- he did his two
songs, thank you very much.

00:32:20.730 --> 00:32:23.350
He was walking out the door,
so we started playing it.

00:32:23.350 --> 00:32:24.770
He walks over to the piano.

00:32:24.770 --> 00:32:27.220
He starts singing, (SINGING)
you took-- (SPEAKING) I said,

00:32:27.220 --> 00:32:29.030
uh-oh, and the rest is history.

00:32:29.030 --> 00:32:30.250
And he nailed it.

00:32:30.250 --> 00:32:32.080
That's how that happened.

00:32:32.080 --> 00:32:35.380
That's why I say this
music is telepathic.

00:32:35.380 --> 00:32:36.650
You have to think.

00:32:36.650 --> 00:32:40.010
Jazz musicians-- let
me just throw this out.

00:32:40.010 --> 00:32:41.920
No offense to anybody--
what you don't know

00:32:41.920 --> 00:32:45.540
is jazz musicians are some
of the smartest people

00:32:45.540 --> 00:32:47.825
in the world outside from this.

00:32:47.825 --> 00:32:48.700
You probably didn't--

00:32:48.700 --> 00:32:49.250
[LAUGHTER]

00:32:49.250 --> 00:32:52.427
No, no-- [INAUDIBLE]
speaks fluent Japanese.

00:32:52.427 --> 00:32:54.010
Now he's starting
the Korean language,

00:32:54.010 --> 00:32:55.430
which is totally different.

00:32:55.430 --> 00:32:57.420
Dr. Willie Ross,
speaks seven languages.

00:32:57.420 --> 00:33:00.490
He's been at Yale
for over 60 years.

00:33:00.490 --> 00:33:04.220
Dr. Don Byrd had four--
you heard of Don Byrd.

00:33:04.220 --> 00:33:07.310
He had four earned
degrees-- no honorary-- plus

00:33:07.310 --> 00:33:11.790
he had a law degree, plus
he was an airplane pilot.

00:33:11.790 --> 00:33:14.310
Keith Jarrett did the
"Goldberg Variations,"

00:33:14.310 --> 00:33:15.277
so forth and so on.

00:33:15.277 --> 00:33:15.860
I could go on.

00:33:15.860 --> 00:33:17.120
We don't have enough time.

00:33:17.120 --> 00:33:21.090
Josh Redman has two
degrees-- MIT and Harvard.

00:33:21.090 --> 00:33:23.630
So what I'm saying
is to play this music

00:33:23.630 --> 00:33:24.800
you've got to be a thinker.

00:33:24.800 --> 00:33:27.220
You have to think fast,
quick on your feet.

00:33:27.220 --> 00:33:30.070
And, as I said before,
not to be redundant,

00:33:30.070 --> 00:33:34.690
it's a pleasure to have all
these great artists on my CD.

00:33:34.690 --> 00:33:36.840
They made me look
good and sound good,

00:33:36.840 --> 00:33:39.150
and I just want to share
that with you again.

00:33:39.150 --> 00:33:40.676
Thanks for your support.

00:33:40.676 --> 00:33:41.800
Now you can finish talking.

00:33:43.722 --> 00:33:45.055
MALE SPEAKER: I think that's it.

00:33:45.055 --> 00:33:47.990
We want to save some time
for the vocal performance,

00:33:47.990 --> 00:33:50.407
so we can get to that
now, but thank you all.

00:33:50.407 --> 00:33:51.990
HAROLD MABERN: All
right, let's do it.

00:33:51.990 --> 00:33:54.435
Thank you.

