00:53:10.050 --> 00:53:10.982
You can't do it.

00:53:10.982 --> 00:53:13.190
I could write down some
notes, but it's not the same.

00:53:13.190 --> 00:53:14.790
It has to come from here.

00:53:14.790 --> 00:53:16.890
Now, Eric Alexander learned
how to play the blues

00:53:16.890 --> 00:53:21.100
because he worked with an
organ player named you see.

00:53:21.100 --> 00:53:24.770
So when you hit a certain
environment, in other words,

00:53:24.770 --> 00:53:27.760
if you want to be a great
three point shooter,

00:53:27.760 --> 00:53:30.445
you've got a practice like Larry
Bird and like Magic Johnson,

00:53:30.445 --> 00:53:35.200
like Michael Jordan
and not Labron James.

00:53:35.200 --> 00:53:37.010
So when we started,
we hated the blues.

00:53:37.010 --> 00:53:38.620
We wanted to play Bebop.

00:53:38.620 --> 00:53:41.029
But as we grew older, we
realized how important

00:53:41.029 --> 00:53:41.570
the blues is.

00:53:41.570 --> 00:53:45.490
See jazz comes from the blues
not the other way around.

00:53:45.490 --> 00:53:46.540
You know what I'm saying?

00:53:46.540 --> 00:53:48.581
When you hear the blues,
you think about BB King,

00:53:48.581 --> 00:53:51.850
you think about Little
Milton Campbell,

00:53:51.850 --> 00:53:55.600
you think about Joe Williams,
you think about Clarence T-Bone

00:53:55.600 --> 00:53:57.080
Walker.

00:53:57.080 --> 00:53:58.530
So the blues is a special part.

00:53:58.530 --> 00:54:01.230
The great Dizzy Gillespie, the
co-progenitor of this music

00:54:01.230 --> 00:54:03.661
said, the difference
between me and Bird-- Bird

00:54:03.661 --> 00:54:04.410
is Charlie Parker.

00:54:04.410 --> 00:54:06.420
He said, Byrd can play
the blues and I couldn't.

00:54:06.420 --> 00:54:06.840
He's right.

00:54:06.840 --> 00:54:08.030
He couldn't play the blues.

00:54:08.030 --> 00:54:10.530
He could play a
blues lick, you see.

00:54:10.530 --> 00:54:13.540
The blues-- like there's a
great pianist named Gene Harris.

00:54:13.540 --> 00:54:15.400
Anybody ever hear
of Gene Harris?

00:54:15.400 --> 00:54:18.010
Now, if I could play
the blues like him,

00:54:18.010 --> 00:54:19.732
I could stick my chest out.

00:54:19.732 --> 00:54:20.940
Now, he could play the blues.

00:54:20.940 --> 00:54:24.400
And he said one time, I'm a
blues piano player with chops.

00:54:24.400 --> 00:54:27.440
People ask me; I said,
I'm a blues piano player

00:54:27.440 --> 00:54:29.530
that understands the
philosophy of jazz, which

00:54:29.530 --> 00:54:30.907
means I can play the blues.

00:54:30.907 --> 00:54:32.740
I can play the boogie
woogie, but I can also

00:54:32.740 --> 00:54:34.420
play the old milestone.

00:54:34.420 --> 00:54:36.240
I can also play [INAUDIBLE].

00:54:36.240 --> 00:54:37.640
So the blues is very special.

00:54:37.640 --> 00:54:39.890
Because all over
the world, no matter

00:54:39.890 --> 00:54:43.540
what your nationality is,
people understand the blues

00:54:43.540 --> 00:54:46.540
all over the world or
anything that's bluesy.

00:54:46.540 --> 00:54:49.420
Gene Ammons, Stanley
Turrentine-- bluesy.

00:54:49.420 --> 00:54:50.420
You see what I'm saying?

00:54:50.420 --> 00:54:53.230
So when you can understand
the blues and play it,

00:54:53.230 --> 00:54:54.460
you're in the right role.

00:54:54.460 --> 00:54:56.930
I hope that answers
your question.

00:54:56.930 --> 00:54:59.540
Anybody else?

00:54:59.540 --> 00:55:00.840
Come on now, don't be shy.

00:55:08.610 --> 00:55:11.142
AUDIENCE: How old were you
when you started playing music?

00:55:11.142 --> 00:55:11.500
HAROLD MABERN: Good question.

00:55:11.500 --> 00:55:12.500
How old was I?

00:55:12.500 --> 00:55:16.870
As I said before, I was
15 and 1/2, 16 years old.

00:55:16.870 --> 00:55:20.080
As I said before,
no shame in my game.

00:55:20.080 --> 00:55:23.960
When guys were
taking Chopin etudes,

00:55:23.960 --> 00:55:26.130
I was chopping, picking,
and pulling cotton.

00:55:26.130 --> 00:55:29.080
BB King talked about that--
that that is the blues.

00:55:29.080 --> 00:55:31.580
And the first thing I learned
how to play, as I said before,

00:55:31.580 --> 00:55:34.560
is a song called "I Stuck
My Dolly-- D-O-L-L-Y--

00:55:34.560 --> 00:55:38.190
dolly's a little baby
doll-- in the Mud."

00:55:38.190 --> 00:55:40.120
And the reason why
I know it's true

00:55:40.120 --> 00:55:42.455
is because I met a young
lady five years ago up

00:55:42.455 --> 00:55:43.080
at [INAUDIBLE].

00:55:43.080 --> 00:55:45.969
She said, Mr. Mabern, how long
have you been playing, and what

00:55:45.969 --> 00:55:47.260
was the first-- and I told her.

00:55:47.260 --> 00:55:48.860
She said, oh, I know that song.

00:55:48.860 --> 00:55:52.180
She said, it's called "I
Stuck My Dolly in the Dirt."

00:55:52.180 --> 00:55:54.430
so it's the same
song with different--

00:55:54.430 --> 00:55:56.575
but I think it comes
from something that Ravel

00:55:56.575 --> 00:55:57.740
that Debussy wrote.

00:55:57.740 --> 00:56:00.451
Let me play it for you quickly.

00:56:00.451 --> 00:56:03.433
This is the first song
that I ever played.

00:56:03.433 --> 00:56:11.385
[MUSIC HAROLD MABERN, " I STUCK
 MY DOLLY IN THE DIRT"]

00:56:20.850 --> 00:56:23.000
So that was my introduction--

00:56:23.000 --> 00:56:23.879
[APPLAUSE]

00:56:23.879 --> 00:56:25.420
I never had formal
training, but see,

00:56:25.420 --> 00:56:28.240
I believe we are all born
with some kind of gift.

00:56:28.240 --> 00:56:31.780
It's up to you to find out and
then grab it when it comes.

00:56:31.780 --> 00:56:34.271
Sometimes you might miss
it, so sprinkle, sprinkle.

00:56:34.271 --> 00:56:36.770
I heard a little girl playing
that, and I went to the piano,

00:56:36.770 --> 00:56:38.230
and learned two songs.

00:56:38.230 --> 00:56:41.060
When I moved to Chicago
and met Spike Lee's dad,

00:56:41.060 --> 00:56:43.117
that's when I really
got into music

00:56:43.117 --> 00:56:44.950
because we were practicing
and playing music

00:56:44.950 --> 00:56:47.960
12 hours a day every
day for five years.

00:56:47.960 --> 00:56:49.830
OK, anybody else?

00:56:49.830 --> 00:56:50.996
Speak up-- don't be shy.

00:56:50.996 --> 00:56:53.287
MALE SPEAKER: Looks like
there's one more on the right.

00:56:57.190 --> 00:57:00.070
AUDIENCE: Hi, thank
you for playing today.

00:57:00.070 --> 00:57:02.960
I find it very interesting
that you're self-taught,

00:57:02.960 --> 00:57:05.540
yet you ended up in
academia teaching

00:57:05.540 --> 00:57:07.212
at William Paterson University.

00:57:07.212 --> 00:57:09.170
I feel like you've seen
both sides of the coin,

00:57:09.170 --> 00:57:10.628
being self-taught,
and you probably

00:57:10.628 --> 00:57:13.110
see tons of students who
have a formal education.

00:57:13.110 --> 00:57:15.920
What would you say are the
advantages and disadvantages

00:57:15.920 --> 00:57:17.850
of each-- school learning
how to play music

00:57:17.850 --> 00:57:21.034
and learning how to play jazz?

00:57:21.034 --> 00:57:22.450
HAROLD MABERN:
Very good question.

00:57:22.450 --> 00:57:24.950
Well, see, even though I've
been in the university for theta

00:57:24.950 --> 00:57:27.570
34 years-- I taught Joe
Farnsworth, Eric Alexander,

00:57:27.570 --> 00:57:31.160
Bill Stewart, Tyshawn Sorey, and
Alexis Cole, the young lady my

00:57:31.160 --> 00:57:32.330
[INAUDIBLE].

00:57:32.330 --> 00:57:35.160
See, this music comes
from what I call

00:57:35.160 --> 00:57:39.160
the 'university of the streets.'
You don't have to go to school

00:57:39.160 --> 00:57:40.460
to learn it.

00:57:40.460 --> 00:57:42.846
Going to school is
just an enhancement.

00:57:42.846 --> 00:57:43.720
You know what I mean?

00:57:43.720 --> 00:57:44.870
I'm the proof of that.

00:57:44.870 --> 00:57:47.650
But I've learned
how to be-- see,

00:57:47.650 --> 00:57:50.040
jazz musicians are
very ubiquitous.

00:57:50.040 --> 00:57:52.230
I wish I had more
time for examples.

00:57:52.230 --> 00:57:53.790
We've heard of the
great Bill Rossi.

00:57:53.790 --> 00:57:55.956
You know that guy that
played with the Seltzers that

00:57:55.956 --> 00:57:57.280
don't sign autographs.

00:57:57.280 --> 00:57:59.861
His best and closest friend
was Julian Cannonball Adderley.

00:57:59.861 --> 00:58:01.110
You didn't know that, did you?

00:58:01.110 --> 00:58:03.170
I wonder why.

00:58:03.170 --> 00:58:05.030
Why would-- Kareem Abdul Jabbar.

00:58:05.030 --> 00:58:07.730
You know who his
best friend was?

00:58:07.730 --> 00:58:10.240
"Freddie" Dewayne Hubbard.

00:58:10.240 --> 00:58:12.340
One of my closest friends
is Dr. Dick Barnett

00:58:12.340 --> 00:58:14.250
who used to play with
the Knickerbockers.

00:58:14.250 --> 00:58:16.770
I wrote a song called "Too
Late, Fall Back, Baby."

00:58:16.770 --> 00:58:18.900
So what I'm saying,
to play this music

00:58:18.900 --> 00:58:20.260
you don't have to go to school.

00:58:20.260 --> 00:58:21.718
You can get all
the books you want.

00:58:21.718 --> 00:58:22.870
It's not the same.

00:58:22.870 --> 00:58:24.060
It comes from the street.

00:58:24.060 --> 00:58:25.480
This is street music.

00:58:25.480 --> 00:58:30.290
For example, we can
go outside of the box.

00:58:30.290 --> 00:58:31.830
Other musicians can't do this.

00:58:31.830 --> 00:58:32.670
We can.

00:58:32.670 --> 00:58:34.854
We can play this.

00:58:34.854 --> 00:58:38.291
[MUSIC - "FRAGILE"]

00:59:01.552 --> 00:59:02.510
Anybody know that song?

00:59:05.350 --> 00:59:06.240
What was that?

00:59:06.240 --> 00:59:06.940
Sting.

00:59:06.940 --> 00:59:08.170
You see what I'm saying?

00:59:10.571 --> 00:59:12.821
But also, here's the thing--
we don't have a whole lot

00:59:12.821 --> 00:59:14.520
of time-- very little.

00:59:14.520 --> 00:59:18.180
When you get yourself involved
with jazz, even if you don't

00:59:18.180 --> 00:59:20.920
play, if you take a course
in Jazz Appreciation,

00:59:20.920 --> 00:59:22.960
being a jazz musician
will teach you

00:59:22.960 --> 00:59:26.272
how to make decisions
in your real life.

00:59:26.272 --> 00:59:27.730
It might sound
funny because you've

00:59:27.730 --> 00:59:29.310
got to be very perceptive.

00:59:29.310 --> 00:59:31.930
You've got to be very
ubiquitous in your thoughts

00:59:31.930 --> 00:59:33.720
and how you make
decisions and stuff.

00:59:33.720 --> 00:59:35.970
So every day I wake
up, I say, dear lord,

00:59:35.970 --> 00:59:38.170
thank you for making
a jazz musician.

00:59:38.170 --> 00:59:40.090
Because I didn't
choose it; it chose me,

00:59:40.090 --> 00:59:42.130
as I said before,
not to be redundant.

00:59:42.130 --> 00:59:45.380
We all are born with some
special kind of gift.

00:59:45.380 --> 00:59:47.200
But it's up to you to
find out what it is.

00:59:47.200 --> 00:59:50.570
And when it comes, sometimes
it might be just a quick flash.

00:59:50.570 --> 00:59:52.060
You've got to grab it.

00:59:52.060 --> 00:59:53.690
So I hope that
answered your question.

00:59:53.690 --> 00:59:55.287
I thank you for coming out.

00:59:55.287 --> 00:59:56.620
MALE SPEAKER: Thank you, Harold.

00:59:56.620 --> 00:59:58.328
HAROLD MABERN: I hope
we can do it again.

00:59:58.328 --> 01:00:02.670
[APPLAUSE]

